                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Public Statement Issued by the Food Administration, September
                        21, 1917</hi>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d559fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">The Official Bulletin</hi>, Washington, Sept. 21, 1917
                        (Vol. 1, No. 113), p. 2.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1917-09-21">September 21, 1917</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>In order to arrange for the distribution of the available sugar in the world, an
                    International Sugar Committee of five members has been formed. Two of the
                    members of this committee were appointed by the Allied Governments, and the men
                    selected for this important work are Sir <persName>Joseph White Todd</persName>
                    and <persName>John V. Drake</persName>, sr.,<note n="2" xml:id="d559fn7">Should
                        read <persName>John Ramsay Drake</persName>.</note> both of whom are
                    familiar with the sugar situation. The two American members of the committee
                    appointed by the Food Administration are <persName>Earl D. Babst</persName>,
                    president of the American Sugar Refining Co., and <persName>William A.
                        Jamison</persName>, of Arbuckle Bros., neither of whom is interested in any
                    way in the production of Cuban sugar. Mr. <persName>George M. Rolph</persName>,
                    head of the Sugar Division of the Food Administration, will be the fifth member
                    of the committee.</p>
                <p>It will be the duty of this committee to arrange for the purchase and
                    distribution of all sugar, whether for the United States or the Allied
                        countries.<note n="3" xml:id="d559fn8">According to a supplementary
                        statement issued Sept. 20 and published Sept. 27, “the activities of the
                        committee will be confined to the importation of sugar from the West Indies
                        and the United States insular possessions.”</note>
                </p>
            </div>
